user:
Sure — a brief fade makes the change less jarring. You can do it entirely in CSS with one transition class and a couple of JavaScript lines:

```css
/* Fade animation */
.fade-transition {
  transition: background-color 0.4s ease, color 0.4s ease;
}
```

```javascript
// Apply the fade class during theme switch
const toggleButton = document.getElementById("themeToggle");

toggleButton.addEventListener("click", () => {
  const html = document.documentElement;
  html.classList.add("fade-transition");

  const current = html.dataset.theme;
  const next = current === "dark" ? "light" : "dark";
  html.dataset.theme = next;
  localStorage.setItem("theme", next);
  toggleButton.textContent = next === "dark" ? "☀️" : "🌙";

  // Remove the class after the transition ends to keep performance smooth
  setTimeout(() => html.classList.remove("fade-transition"), 500);
});
```

**How it works**

1. Adds a `.fade-transition` class right before the color swap so background and text colors ease into the new values.  
2. Removes the class afterward to prevent stacking multiple transitions.  
3. The delay (`500 ms`) can be shorter or longer, depending on how gentle you want the effect.

It’s an easy polish step that makes the theme switch feel deliberate and calm on both mobile and desktop.
